    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-10-31T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-10-31T13:00:00-05:00" n="57"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d57">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.8890/9735/6: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Afghanistan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Engert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Kabul</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-10-31T22:00:00+04:00"
                            >October 31, 1942—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 2—2:36 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>98. British Minister<note n="17" xml:id="d57fn17">Sir Francis Wylie.</note> and I
                    have right along been in entire agreement re subject of your 52, October 27. He
                    feels as you and I that if we can accommodate Afghan Government in small matters
                    we should do so. We need, of course, make no promises re 1942 lamb skin crop …
                    Incidentally British Minister states India does not want Afghan wool.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Engert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
